title.narrative: CHILD PROTECTION SERVICES

description.narrative: By 2022, key institutions and service providers have increased capacity to boost the coverage and quality of specialised child protection services, which contributes to Operations Support To Programme Delivery, Promotion Of Care, Mental Health And Psychosocial Well-Being And Justice, Protection From Violence, Exploitation, Abuse And Neglect, Protection From Violence, Exploitation, Abuse And Neglect (Covid). UNICEF aims to achieve this through Community Engagement, Social And Behaviour Change, Operational Support To Programme Delivery, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2022, all boys and girls in Myanmar are covered by a child protection system that fosters prevention and timely response to and recovery from violence, exploitation and separation from family.

title.narrative: By 2022, key institutions and service providers have increased capacity to boost the coverage and quality of specialisedchild protection services

description.narrative: Widespread violence across the country continued to threaten safe access to critical humanitarian services for the affected population. Due to humanitarian access restrictions, community-based and local organizations were mobilized for service delivery. Operational risks associated with service delivery remained a concern. With the introduction of Child Protection AOR, UNICEF contributed to sub-national coordination in new areas to meet increasing demand for coordinated services/assistance. While service delivery has generally slowed down due to security and COVID situations, UNICEF and partners using innovative approaches delivered child protection services and supplies to vulnerable children including legal aid, remote counselling and child-friendly spaces activities. | Status:Constrained | As-of Date:17/12/2021
